- Note on piano‑first preference: my self‑introduction prefers piano‑first recordings, and neither candidate explicitly advertises a piano focus. That absence reinforces choosing the disc whose stated attributes best match my other hard requirements (transients, early‑70s mids, low reverb, minimal overdubs, clear separation)—i.e., CD 2—because it at least preserves the sound‑stage and dynamics that would allow a piano (if present) to retain attack and presence rather than be washed by reverb or dense layering.
Conclusion: CD 2 best preserves the technical and aesthetic traits I specified (transient preservation, warm analogue mids, low‑reverb close vocals, minimal overdubs, clear separation and LP‑style sequencing) and avoids the production elements I dislike (roomy reverb, guitar‑dominant midrange, lush crowded layering, and heavier sheen/compression). For these concrete, feature‑level reasons I select CD 2 and reject CD 1.

